<section id="faq" class="faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-tag">FAQ</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Technical Details</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item" open>
        <summary>
          <span>What is Unbound — technically?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Unbound is a Go wrapper around the <strong>Zapret 2</strong> engine (winws2 binary) and the <strong>WinDivert 2.2</strong> kernel packet filter. It provides a system-tray GUI that configures, launches, and monitors winws2 — the same DPI-evasion engine used by GoodbyeDPI and Zapret, but with automated profile selection and conflict detection.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>How does the WinDivert engine work?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>WinDivert installs a WFP (Windows Filtering Platform) callout driver at <strong>L3 (Network Layer)</strong> and <strong>L4 (Transport Layer)</strong>. It intercepts raw TCP/UDP packets before they reach the network stack. Winws2 then applies evasion techniques — TCP desynchronization, packet reordering (multidisorder), TTL manipulation, and HTTP/DPI-specific field obfuscation — before reinjecting modified packets. The target server reassembles the stream normally; DPI systems cannot reconstruct the original TLS handshake.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>What filter levels does it operate on?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p><strong>L3 (Network):</strong> IP-level filtering by destination/source address. <strong>L4 (Transport):</strong> TCP/UDP port and flag filtering. WinDivert captures packets at these layers — it does not operate at L7 (Application). DPI evasion is achieved by manipulating transport-layer characteristics (TCP sequence numbers, TTL, window size) that cause DPI parsers to lose stream synchronization while the endpoint TCP stack recovers correctly.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>How is this different from a VPN?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>A VPN creates an encrypted tunnel to a remote server, routing <em>all</em> traffic through it — adding latency and reducing bandwidth. Unbound modifies only packets destined for domains on the blocklist. Everything else — local banking, government services, CDNs — traverses the network unmodified. Zero overhead for non-blocked traffic. No remote infrastructure involved.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>Why are administrator privileges required?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>WinDivert is a kernel-mode WFP callout driver. Installing and binding it requires <strong>SeLoadDriverPrivilege</strong> — an admin-only right. Once installed, the driver persists across reboots. Unbound registers a Task Scheduler entry for silent startup (no UAC prompt on boot) and runs as a background process in the system tray.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>What about macOS and Linux support?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p><strong>macOS:</strong> Uses <strong>SpoofDPI</strong> — a SOCKS5 proxy approach with system network configuration. <strong>Linux:</strong> Uses <strong>nfqws</strong> with iptables/nftables NFQUEUE for packet-level manipulation (equivalent to WinDivert on Windows). The Go desktop wrapper handles launch automation on both platforms. A standalone <strong>Rust CLI</strong> is also available for headless deployment.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>
          <span>What conflicts should I be aware of?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Since WinDivert operates at L3, concurrent packet-level filters cause undefined behavior. Unbound detects and blocks launch when the following are running: <strong>GoodbyeDPI</strong>, <strong>Zapret</strong> (nfqws/winws instances), <strong>OpenVPN</strong> (TAP adapter conflicts), <strong>Cloudflare WARP</strong>, and commercial VPN clients (ExpressVPN, NordVPN). Close conflicting processes before launching.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

